# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: brayton-cycle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] An **absorption refrigerator** is a refrigerator that uses a heat source to provide the energy needed to drive the cooling process.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Solar energy, burning a fossil fuel, waste heat from factories, and district heating systems are examples of heat sources that can be used.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator uses two coolants, the first coolant performing evaporative cooling before being absorbed into the second coolant.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Heat is then needed to reset the two coolants to their initial states.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are commonly used in recreational vehicles (RVs), campers, and caravans because the heat required to power them can be provided by either a propane fuel burner, a low-voltage DC electric heater (from a battery or vehicle electrical system) or a mains-powered electric heater.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators can also be used to air-condition buildings using the waste heat from a gas turbine or water heater in the building.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Using waste heat from a gas turbine makes the turbine very efficient because it first produces electricity, then hot water, and finally, air-conditioning—trigeneration.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Unlike more common vapor-compression refrigeration systems, an absorption refrigerator has no moving parts.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigerators are an alternative to compressor refrigerators where electricity is unreliable, costly, or unavailable; where noise from the compressor is problematic; or where surplus heat is available.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In 1748 in Glasgow, William Cullen invented the basis for modern refrigeration, although he is not credited with a usable application.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] More on history of refrigeration can be found in the paragraph Refrigeration Research on page Refrigeration.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption refrigeration uses the same principle as adsorption refrigeration, which was invented by Michael Faraday in 1821.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Instead of using a solid adsorber, an absorber in an absorption system absorbs the refrigerant vapour into a liquid.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Absorption cooling was invented by the French scientist Ferdinand Carré in 1858.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The original design used water and sulphuric acid.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The principle was enhanced with a three-fluid configuration in 1922 by Baltzar von Platen and Carl Munters, two students at the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] This "Platen-Munters" design can operate without a pump.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Commercial production began in 1923 by the newly-formed company *AB Arctic*, which was bought by Electrolux in 1925.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In the 1960s, absorption refrigeration saw a renaissance due to the substantial demand for refrigerators for caravans.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] AB Electrolux later established a subsidiary in the United States, named Dometic Sales Corporation.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The company marketed refrigerators for recreational vehicles (RVs) under the *Dometic* brand.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In 2001, Electrolux sold most of its leisure products line to the venture-capital company EQT which created *Dometic* as a stand-alone company.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Dometic still sold absorption fridges as of July 2025.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In 1926, Albert Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd proposed an alternative design known as the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] At the 2007 TED Conference, Adam Grosser presented his research of an "intermittent absorption" vaccine refrigeration unit for use in third world countries.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator is a small unit placed over a campfire, that can later be used to cool 15 litres (3.3 imp gal; 4.0 US gal) of water to just above freezing for 24 hours in a 30 °C (86 °F) environment.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The concept was similar to an early refrigeration device known as an Icyball.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Common absorption refrigerators use a refrigerant with a very low boiling point (less than −18 °C (0 °F)) just like compressor refrigerators.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Compression refrigerators typically use an HCFC or HFC, while absorption refrigerators typically use ammonia or water and need at least a second fluid able to absorb the coolant, the *absorbent*, respectively water (for ammonia) or brine (for water).
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Both types use evaporative cooling: when the refrigerant evaporates (boils), it takes some heat away with it, providing the cooling effect.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The main difference between the two systems is the way the refrigerant is changed from a gas back into a liquid so that the cycle can repeat.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] An absorption refrigerator changes the gas back into a liquid using a method that needs only heat, and has no moving parts other than the fluids.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The system thus silently provides for the mechanical circulation of the liquid without a usual pump.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] A third fluid, gaseous, is usually added to avoid pressure concerns when condensation occurs (see below).
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In comparison, a compressor based heat pump works by pumping refrigerant gas from an evaporator to a condenser.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] This reduces the pressure and boiling temperature in the evaporator and increases the pressure and condensing temperature in the condenser.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Energy from an electric motor or internal combustion engine is required to operate the compressor pump.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Compressing the refrigerant uses this energy to do work on the gas, increasing its temperature.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The warm, high pressure gas then enters the condenser where it undergoes a phase change to a liquid and releases heat to the condenser's surroundings.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Warm liquid refrigerant moves from the high pressure condenser to the low pressure evaporator via an expansion valve, also known as a throttling valve or a Joule-Thomson valve.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The expansion valve partially vaporizes the refrigerant cooling it via evaporative cooling, and the resulting vapor is cooled via expansive cooling.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] This is a combination of Joule-Thomson cooling and work done by the expanding gas, both at the expense of the internal energy of the gas.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The cold, low pressure liquid refrigerant will now absorb heat from the evaporator's surroundings and vaporize.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The resulting gas enters the compressor, and the cycle begins again.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] A simple absorption refrigeration system common in large commercial plants uses a solution of lithium bromide or lithium chloride salt and water.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Water under low pressure is evaporated from the coils that are to be chilled.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The water is absorbed by a lithium bromide/water solution.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The system drives the water out of the lithium bromide solution with heat.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Another variant uses air, water, and a salt water solution.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The intake of warm, moist air is passed through a sprayed solution of salt water.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The spray lowers the humidity but does not significantly change the temperature.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The less humid, warm air is then passed through an evaporative cooler, consisting of a spray of fresh water, which cools and re-humidifies the air.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Humidity is removed from the cooled air with another spray of salt solution, providing the outlet of cool, dry air.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The salt solution is regenerated by heating it under low pressure, causing water to evaporate.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The water evaporated from the salt solution is re-condensed, and rerouted back to the evaporative cooler.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] A single-pressure absorption refrigerator takes advantage of the fact that a liquid's evaporation rate depends upon the *partial* pressure of the vapor above the liquid and goes up with lower partial pressure.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The refrigerator uses three substances: ammonia, hydrogen gas, and water.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The cycle is closed, with all hydrogen, water and ammonia collected and endlessly reused.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The cooling cycle starts with liquid ammonia at room temperature entering the evaporator.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The volume of the evaporator is greater than the volume of the liquid, with the excess space occupied by a mixture of gaseous ammonia and hydrogen.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The presence of hydrogen lowers the partial pressure of the ammonia gas, thus lowering the evaporation point of the liquid below the temperature of the refrigerator's interior.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Ammonia evaporates, taking a small amount of heat from the liquid and lowering the liquid's temperature.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] It continues to evaporate, while the large enthalpy of vaporization (heat) flows from the warmer refrigerator interior to the cooler liquid ammonia and then to more ammonia gas.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In the next two steps, the ammonia gas is separated from the hydrogen so it can be reused.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The next step separates the ammonia and water.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The ammonia/water solution flows to the generator (boiler), where heat is applied to boil off the ammonia, leaving most of the water (which has a higher boiling point) behind.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] Some water vapor and bubbles remain mixed with the ammonia; this water is removed in the final separation step, by passing it through the separator, an uphill series of twisted pipes with minor obstacles to pop the bubbles, allowing the water vapor to condense and drain back to the generator.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The pure ammonia gas then enters the condenser.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] In this heat exchanger, the hot ammonia gas transfers its heat to the outside air, which is below the boiling point of the full-pressure ammonia, and therefore condenses.
[src:brayton-cycle/absorption-refrigerator] The condensed (liquid) ammonia flows down to be mixed with the hydrogen gas released from the absorption step, repeating the cycle.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] An **adiabatic process** (*adiabatic* from Ancient Greek ἀδιάβατος*(*adiábatos*)* 'impassable') is a type of thermodynamic process whereby a transfer of energy between the thermodynamic system and its environment is accompanied neither by a transfer of entropy nor of amounts of constituents.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Unlike an isothermal process, an adiabatic process transfers energy to the surroundings only as work and/or mass flow.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] As a key concept in thermodynamics, the adiabatic process supports the theory that explains the first law of thermodynamics.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The opposite term to "adiabatic" is *diabatic*.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Some chemical and physical processes occur too rapidly for energy to enter or leave the system as heat, allowing a convenient "adiabatic approximation".
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] For example, the adiabatic flame temperature uses this approximation to calculate the upper limit of flame temperature by assuming combustion loses no heat to its surroundings.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In meteorology, adiabatic expansion and cooling of moist air, which can be triggered by winds flowing up and over a mountain for example, can cause the water vapor pressure to exceed the saturation vapor pressure.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Expansion and cooling beyond the saturation vapor pressure is often idealized as a *pseudo-adiabatic process* whereby excess vapor instantly precipitates into water droplets.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The change in temperature of air undergoing pseudo-adiabatic expansion differs from air undergoing adiabatic expansion because latent heat is released by precipitation.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] A process without transfer of thermal energy (heat) to or from a system, so that *Q* = 0, is called adiabatic, and such a system is said to be adiabatically isolated.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The simplifying assumption frequently made is that a process is adiabatic.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] For example, the compression of a gas within a cylinder of an engine is assumed to occur so rapidly that on the time scale of the compression process, little of the system's energy can be transferred out as heat to the surroundings.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Even though the cylinders are not insulated and are quite conductive, that process is idealized to be adiabatic.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The same can be said to be true for the expansion process of such a system.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The assumption of adiabatic isolation is useful and often combined with other such idealizations to calculate a good first approximation of a system's behaviour.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] For example, according to Laplace, when sound travels in a gas, there is no time for heat conduction in the medium, and so the propagation of sound is adiabatic.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] For such an adiabatic process, the modulus of elasticity (Young's modulus) can be expressed as *E* = *γP*, where γ is the ratio of specific heats at constant pressure and at constant volume ( *γ* = ⁠*Cp*/*Cv*⁠) and *P* is the pressure of the gas.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] For a closed system, one may write the first law of thermodynamics as Δ*U* = *Q* − *W*, where Δ*U* denotes the change of the system's internal energy, Q the quantity of energy added to it as heat, and W the work done by the system on its surroundings.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Naturally occurring adiabatic processes are irreversible (entropy is produced).
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The transfer of energy as work into an adiabatically isolated system can be imagined as being of two idealized extreme kinds.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In one such kind, no entropy is produced within the system (no friction, viscous dissipation, etc.), and the work is only pressure-volume work (denoted by *P* d*V*).
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In nature, this ideal kind occurs only approximately because it demands an infinitely slow process and no sources of dissipation.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The other extreme kind of work is isochoric work (d*V* = 0), for which energy is added as work solely through friction or viscous dissipation within the system.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] A stirrer that transfers energy to a viscous fluid of an adiabatically isolated system with rigid walls, without phase change, will cause a rise in temperature of the fluid, but that work is not recoverable.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The second law of thermodynamics observes that a natural process, of transfer of energy as work, always consists at least of isochoric work and often both of these extreme kinds of work.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Every natural process, adiabatic or not, is irreversible, with Δ*S* > 0, as friction or viscosity are always present to some extent.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic compression of a gas causes a rise in temperature of the gas.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion against pressure, or a spring, causes a drop in temperature.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In contrast, free expansion is an isothermal process for an ideal gas.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] This finds practical application in diesel engines which rely on the lack of heat dissipation during the compression stroke to elevate the fuel vapor temperature sufficiently to ignite it.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic compression occurs in the Earth's atmosphere when an air mass descends, for example, in a Katabatic wind, Foehn wind, or Chinook wind flowing downhill over a mountain range.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] When a parcel of air descends, the pressure on the parcel increases.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Because of this increase in pressure, the parcel's volume decreases and its temperature increases as work is done on the parcel of air, thus increasing its internal energy, which manifests itself by a rise in the temperature of that mass of air.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The parcel of air can only slowly dissipate the energy by conduction or radiation (heat), and to a first approximation it can be considered adiabatically isolated and the process an adiabatic process.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs when the pressure on an adiabatically isolated system is decreased, allowing it to expand in size, thus causing it to do work on its surroundings.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] When the pressure applied on a parcel of gas is reduced, the gas in the parcel is allowed to expand; as the volume increases, the temperature falls as its internal energy decreases.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion occurs in the Earth's atmosphere with orographic lifting and lee waves, and this can form pilei or lenticular clouds.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Due in part to adiabatic expansion in mountainous areas, snowfall actually occurs in some parts of the Sahara desert.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Adiabatic expansion does not have to involve a fluid.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] One technique used to reach very low temperatures (thousandths and even millionths of a degree above absolute zero) is via adiabatic demagnetisation, where the change in magnetic field on a magnetic material is used to provide adiabatic expansion.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Also, the contents of an expanding universe can be described (to first order) as an adiabatically expanding fluid.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Rising magma also undergoes adiabatic expansion before eruption, particularly significant in the case of magmas that rise quickly from great depths such as kimberlites.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In the Earth's convecting mantle (the asthenosphere) beneath the lithosphere, the mantle temperature is approximately an adiabat.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The slight decrease in temperature with shallowing depth is due to the decrease in pressure the shallower the material is in the Earth.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Such temperature changes can be quantified using the ideal gas law, or the hydrostatic equation for atmospheric processes.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In practice, no process is truly adiabatic.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Many processes rely on a large difference in time scales of the process of interest and the rate of heat dissipation across a system boundary, and thus are approximated by using an adiabatic assumption.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] There is always some heat loss, as no perfect insulators exist.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Here CP is the specific heat for constant pressure, CV is the specific heat for constant volume, and f is the number of degrees of freedom (3 for a monatomic gas, 5 for a diatomic gas or a gas of linear molecules such as carbon dioxide).
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] For a monatomic ideal gas, *γ* = ⁠5/3⁠, and for a diatomic gas (such as nitrogen and oxygen, the main components of air), *γ* = ⁠7/5⁠.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Note that the above formula is only applicable to classical ideal gases (that is, gases far above absolute zero temperature) and not Bose–Einstein or Fermi gases.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] where T is the absolute or thermodynamic temperature.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The compression stroke in a gasoline engine can be used as an example of adiabatic compression.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] so the adiabatic constant for this example is about 6.31 Pa·m4.2 .
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The gas is now compressed to a 0.1 L (0.0001 m3) volume, which we assume happens quickly enough that no heat enters or leaves the gas through the walls.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] We can solve for the temperature of the compressed gas in the engine cylinder as well, using the ideal gas law, P V = n R T (n is amount of gas in moles and R the gas constant for that gas).
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] That is a final temperature of 753 K, or 479 °C, or 896 °F, well above the ignition point of many fuels.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] A diesel engine operates under even more extreme conditions, with compression ratios of 16:1 or more being typical, in order to provide a very high gas pressure, which ensures immediate ignition of the injected fuel.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] For an adiabatic free expansion of an ideal gas, the gas is contained in an insulated container and then allowed to expand in a vacuum.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Because there is no external pressure for the gas to expand against, the work done by or on the system is zero.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Since this process does not involve any heat transfer or work, the first law of thermodynamics then implies that the net internal energy change of the system is zero.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] For an ideal gas, the temperature remains constant because the internal energy only depends on temperature in that case.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Since at constant temperature, the entropy is proportional to the volume, the entropy increases in this case, therefore this process is irreversible.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The definition of an adiabatic process is that heat transfer to the system is zero, *δQ* = 0.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] where d*U* is the change in the internal energy of the system and *δW* is work done *by* the system.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Any work (*δW*) done must be done at the expense of internal energy U, since no heat δQ is being supplied from the surroundings.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] However, P does not remain constant during an adiabatic process but instead changes along with V.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] It is desired to know how the values of d*P* and d*V* relate to each other as the adiabatic process proceeds.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] where α is the number of degrees of freedom divided by 2, R is the universal gas constant and n is the number of moles in the system (a constant).
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Equation (a4) is often expressed as d*U* = *n CV*d*T* because *CV* = *α R* .
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] An adiabat is a curve of constant entropy in a diagram.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Some properties of adiabats on a *P* – *V* diagram are indicated.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] These properties may be read from the classical behaviour of ideal gases, except in the region where P V becomes small (low temperature), where quantum effects become important.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Each adiabat intersects each isotherm exactly once.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] An adiabat looks similar to an isotherm, except that during an expansion, an adiabat loses more pressure than an isotherm, so it has a steeper inclination (more vertical).
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] If isotherms are concave towards the north-east direction (45° from V axis), then adiabats are concave towards the east north-east (31° from V axisaxis).
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] If adiabats and isotherms are graphed at regular intervals of entropy and temperature, respectively (like altitude on a contour map), then as the eye moves towards the axes (towards the south-west), it sees the density of isotherms stay constant, but it sees the density of adiabats grow.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The exception is very near absolute zero, where the density of adiabats drops sharply and they become rare (see Nernst's theorem).
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The term *adiabatic* (/ˌædiəˈbætɪk/) is an anglicization of the Greek term ἀδιάβατος "impassable" (used by Xenophon of rivers).
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] It is used in the thermodynamic sense by Rankine (1866), and adopted by Maxwell in 1871 (explicitly attributing the term to Rankine).
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The etymological origin corresponds here to an impossibility of transfer of energy as heat and of transfer of matter across the wall.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The Greek word ἀδιάβατος is formed from privative ἀ- ("not") and διαβατός, "passable", in turn deriving from διά ("through"), and βαῖνειν ("to walk, go, come").
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Furthermore, in atmospheric thermodynamics, a diabatic process is one in which heat is exchanged.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] An adiabatic process is the opposite – a process in which no heat is exchanged.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process has been important for thermodynamics since its early days.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] It was important in the work of Joule because it provided a way of nearly directly relating quantities of heat and work.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Energy can enter or leave a thermodynamic system enclosed by walls that prevent mass transfer only as heat or work.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Therefore, a quantity of work in such a system can be related almost directly to an equivalent quantity of heat in a cycle of two limbs.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The first limb is an isochoric adiabatic work process increasing the system's internal energy; the second, an isochoric and workless heat transfer returning the system to its original state.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Accordingly, Rankine measured quantity of heat in units of work, rather than as a calorimetric quantity.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In 1854, Rankine used a quantity that he called "the thermodynamic function" that later was called entropy, and at that time he wrote also of the "curve of no transmission of heat", which he later called an adiabatic curve.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Besides its two isothermal limbs, Carnot's cycle has two adiabatic limbs.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] For the foundations of thermodynamics, the conceptual importance of this was emphasized by Bryan, by Carathéodory, and by Born.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The reason is that calorimetry presupposes a type of temperature as already defined before the statement of the first law of thermodynamics, such as one based on empirical scales.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Such a presupposition involves making the distinction between empirical temperature and absolute temperature.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Rather, the definition of absolute thermodynamic temperature is best left till the second law is available as a conceptual basis.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In the eighteenth century, the law of conservation of energy was not yet fully formulated or established, and the nature of heat was debated.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] One approach to these problems was to regard heat, measured by calorimetry, as a primary substance that is conserved in quantity.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] By the middle of the nineteenth century, it was recognized as a form of energy, and the law of conservation of energy was thereby also recognized.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The view that eventually established itself, and is currently regarded as right, is that the law of conservation of energy is a primary axiom, and that heat is to be analyzed as consequential.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In this light, heat cannot be a component of the total energy of a single body because it is not a state variable but, rather, a variable that describes a transfer between two bodies.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The adiabatic process is important because it is a logical ingredient of this current view.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] This present article is written from the viewpoint of macroscopic thermodynamics, and the word *adiabatic* is used in this article in the traditional way of thermodynamics, introduced by Rankine.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] It is pointed out in the present article that, for example, if a compression of a gas is rapid, then there is little time for heat transfer to occur, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In this sense, a rapid compression of a gas is sometimes approximately or loosely said to be *adiabatic*, though often far from isentropic, even when the gas is not adiabatically isolated by a definite wall.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Some authors, like Pippard, recommend using "adiathermal" to refer to processes where no heat-exchange occurs (such as Joule expansion), and "adiabatic" to reversible quasi-static adiathermal processes (so that rapid compression of a gas is *not* "adiabatic").
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] And Laidler has summarized the complicated etymology of "adiabatic".
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Quantum mechanics and quantum statistical mechanics, however, use the word *adiabatic* in a very different sense, one that can at times seem almost opposite to the classical thermodynamic sense.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In quantum theory, the word *adiabatic* can mean something perhaps near isentropic, or perhaps near quasi-static, but the usage of the word is very different between the two disciplines.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] On the one hand, in quantum theory, if a perturbative element of compressive work is done almost infinitely slowly (that is to say quasi-statically), it is said to have been done *adiabatically*.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The idea is that the shapes of the eigenfunctions change slowly and continuously, so that no quantum jump is triggered, and the change is virtually reversible.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] While the occupation numbers are unchanged, nevertheless there is change in the energy levels of one-to-one corresponding, pre- and post-compression, eigenstates.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Thus a perturbative element of work has been done without heat transfer and without introduction of random change within the system.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In that theory, such a rapid change is said not to be *adiabatic*, and the contrary word *diabatic* is applied to it.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Recent research suggests that the power absorbed from the perturbation corresponds to the rate of these non-adiabatic transitions.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] This corresponds to the classical process of energy transfer in the form of heat, but with the relative time scales reversed in the quantum case.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Quantum adiabatic processes occur over relatively long time scales, while classical adiabatic processes occur over relatively short time scales.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] It should also be noted that the concept of 'heat' (in reference to the quantity of thermal energy transferred) breaks down at the quantum level, and the specific form of energy (typically electromagnetic) must be considered instead.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The small or negligible absorption of energy from the perturbation in a quantum adiabatic process provides a good justification for identifying it as the quantum analogue of adiabatic processes in classical thermodynamics, and for the reuse of the term.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] In classical thermodynamics, such a rapid change would still be called adiabatic because the system is adiabatically isolated, and there is no transfer of energy as heat.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The strong irreversibility of the change, due to viscosity or other entropy production, does not impinge on this classical usage.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] Thus for a mass of gas, in macroscopic thermodynamics, words are so used that a compression is sometimes loosely or approximately said to be adiabatic if it is rapid enough to avoid significant heat transfer, even if the system is not adiabatically isolated.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] But in quantum statistical theory, a compression is not called adiabatic if it is rapid, even if the system is adiabatically isolated in the classical thermodynamic sense of the term.
[src:brayton-cycle/adiabatic-process] The words are used differently in the two disciplines, as stated just above.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:brayton-cycle/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] An **airbreathing jet engine** (or **ducted jet engine**) is a jet engine in which the exhaust gas which supplies jet propulsion is atmospheric air, which is taken in, compressed, heated, and expanded back to atmospheric pressure through a propelling nozzle.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Compression may be provided by a gas turbine, as in the original turbojet and newer turbofan, or arise solely from the ram pressure of the vehicle's velocity, as with the ramjet and pulsejet.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] All practical airbreathing jet engines heat the air by burning fuel.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Alternatively a heat exchanger may be used, as in a nuclear-powered jet engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Most modern jet engines are turbofans, which are more fuel efficient than turbojets because the thrust supplied by the gas turbine is augmented by bypass air passing through a ducted fan.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The original air-breathing gas turbine jet engine was the turbojet.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] It was a concept brought to life by two engineers, Frank Whittle in England UK and Hans von Ohain in Germany.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The turbojet compresses and heats air and then exhausts it as a high speed, high temperature jet to create thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] While these engines are capable of giving high thrust levels, they are most efficient at very high speeds (over Mach 1), due to the low-mass-flow, high speed nature of the jet exhaust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Modern turbofans are a development of the turbojet; they are basically turbojets that include a new section called the *fan stage*.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Rather than using all their exhaust gases to provide direct thrust like a turbojet, turbofan engines extract some of the power from the exhaust gases inside the engine and use it to power the fan stage.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The fan stage accelerates a large volume of air through a duct, bypassing the *engine core* (the actual gas turbine component of the engine), and expelling it at the rear as a jet, creating thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] A proportion of the air that comes through the fan stage enters the engine core rather than being ducted to the rear, and is thus compressed and heated; some of the energy is extracted to power the compressors and fans, while the remainder is exhausted at the rear.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] This high-speed, hot-gas exhaust blends with the low speed, cool-air exhaust from the fan stage, and both contribute to the overall thrust of the engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Depending on what proportion of cool air is bypassed around the engine core, a turbofan can be called *low-bypass*, *high-bypass*, or *very-high-bypass* engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Over the last several decades, there has been a move towards *very high bypass* engines, which use fans far larger than the engine core itself, which is typically a modern, high efficiency two or three-spool design.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Airbreathing jet engines are nearly always internal combustion engines that obtain propulsion from the combustion of fuel inside the engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Oxygen present in the atmosphere is used to oxidise a fuel source, typically a hydrocarbon-based jet fuel.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The burning mixture expands greatly in volume, driving heated air through a propelling nozzle.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Two engineers, Frank Whittle in the UK and Hans von Ohain in Germany, developed the **turbojet** concept independently into practical engines during the late 1930s.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojets consist of an inlet, a compressor, a combustor, a turbine (that drives the compressor) and a propelling nozzle.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojets have a low propulsive efficiency below about Mach 2 and produce a lot of jet noise, both a result of the very high velocity of the exhaust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Modern jet propelled aircraft are powered by turbofans.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] These engines, with their lower exhaust velocities, produce less jet noise and use less fuel.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojets are still used to power medium range cruise missiles due to their high exhaust speed, low frontal area, which reduces drag, and relative simplicity, which reduces cost.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The low pressure compressor (LPC), usually known as a fan, compresses air into a bypass duct whilst its inner portion supercharges the core compressor.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The fan is often an integral part of a multi-stage core LPC.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The bypass airflow either passes to a separate 'cold nozzle' or mixes with low pressure turbine exhaust gases, before expanding through a 'mixed flow nozzle'.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] In the 1960s there was little difference between civil and military jet engines, apart from the use of afterburning in some (supersonic) applications.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Today, turbofans are used for airliners because they have an exhaust speed that is better matched to the subsonic flight speed of the airliner.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] At airliner flight speeds, the exhaust speed from a turbojet engine is excessively high and wastes energy.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The lower exhaust speed from a turbofan gives better fuel consumption.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The increased airflow from the fan gives higher thrust at low speeds.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The lower exhaust speed also gives much lower jet noise.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The comparatively large frontal fan has several effects.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Compared to a turbojet of identical thrust, a turbofan has a much larger air mass flow rate and the flow through the bypass duct generates a significant fraction of the thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The additional duct air has not been ignited, which gives it a slow speed, but no extra fuel is needed to provide this thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Instead, the energy is taken from the central core, which gives it also a reduced exhaust speed.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The average velocity of the mixed exhaust air is thus reduced (low specific thrust) which is less wasteful of energy but reduces the top speed.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Overall, a turbofan can be much more fuel efficient and quieter, and it turns out that the fan also allows greater net thrust to be available at slow speeds.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Thus civil turbofans today have a low exhaust speed (low *specific thrust* – net thrust divided by airflow) to keep jet noise to a minimum and to improve fuel efficiency.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Consequently, the bypass ratio (bypass flow divided by core flow) is relatively high (ratios from 4:1 up to 8:1 are common), with the Rolls-Royce Trent XWB approaching 10:1.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Only a single fan stage is required, because a low specific thrust implies a low fan pressure ratio.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbofans designed for subsonic civilian aircraft also usually have a just a single front fan, because their additional thrust is generated by a large additional mass of air which is only moderately compressed, rather than a smaller amount of air which is greatly compressed.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Military turbofans, however, have a relatively high specific thrust, to maximize the thrust for a given frontal area, jet noise being of less concern in military uses relative to civil uses.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Multistage fans are normally needed to reach the relatively high fan pressure ratio needed for high specific thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Although high turbine inlet temperatures are often employed, the bypass ratio tends to be low, usually significantly less than 2.0.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turboprop engines are jet engine derivatives, still gas turbines, that extract work from the hot-exhaust jet to turn a rotating shaft, which is then used to produce thrust by some other means.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] While not strictly jet engines in that they rely on an auxiliary mechanism to produce thrust, turboprops are very similar to other turbine-based jet engines, and are often described as such.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] In turboprop engines, a portion of the engine's thrust is produced by spinning a propeller, rather than relying solely on high-speed jet exhaust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Producing thrust both ways, turboprops are occasionally referred to as a type of hybrid jet engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] They differ from turbofans in that a traditional propeller, rather than a ducted fan, provides the majority of thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Most turboprops use gear-reduction between the turbine and the propeller.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] (Geared turbofans also feature gear reduction, but they are less common.) The hot-jet exhaust is an important minority of thrust, and maximum thrust is obtained by matching the two thrust contributions.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turboprops generally have better performance than turbojets or turbofans at low speeds where propeller efficiency is high, but become increasingly noisy and inefficient at high speeds.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turboshaft engines are very similar to turboprops, differing in that nearly all energy in the exhaust is extracted to spin the rotating shaft, which is used to power machinery rather than a propeller, they therefore generate little to no jet thrust and are often used to power helicopters.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] A propfan engine (also called a "propjet", "unducted fan", "open rotor", or "ultra-high bypass") is a jet engine that uses its gas generator to power an exposed fan, similar to turboprop engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Like turboprop engines, propfans generate most of their thrust from the propeller and not the exhaust jet.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The primary difference between turboprop and propfan design is that the propeller blades on a propfan are highly swept to allow them to operate at speeds around Mach 0.8, which is competitive with modern commercial turbofans.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] These engines have the fuel efficiency advantages of turboprops with the performance capability of commercial turbofans.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] While significant research and testing (including flight testing) has been conducted on propfans, none have entered production.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The various components named above have constraints on how they are put together to generate the most efficiency or performance.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The performance and efficiency of an engine can never be taken in isolation; for example fuel/distance efficiency of a supersonic jet engine maximises at about Mach 2, whereas the drag for the vehicle carrying it is increasing as a square law and has much extra drag in the transonic region.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The highest fuel efficiency for the overall vehicle is thus typically around Mach 0.85.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The thermodynamics of a typical air-breathing jet engine are modeled approximately by a **Brayton Cycle** which is a thermodynamic cycle that describes the workings of the gas turbine engine, which is the basis of the airbreathing jet engine and others.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is named after George Brayton (1830–1892), the American engineer who developed it, although it was originally proposed and patented by Englishman John Barber in 1791.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is also sometimes known as the **Joule cycle**.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The nominal net thrust quoted for a jet engine usually refers to the Sea Level Static (SLS) condition, either for the International Standard Atmosphere (ISA) or a hot day condition (e.g.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] As an example, the GE90-76B has a take-off static thrust of 76,000 lbf (360 kN) at SLS, ISA+15 °C.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Naturally, net thrust will decrease with altitude, because of the lower air density.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] There is also, however, a flight speed effect.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Initially as the aircraft gains speed down the runway, there will be little increase in nozzle pressure and temperature, because the ram rise in the intake is very small.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] There will also be little change in mass flow.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Consequently, nozzle gross thrust initially only increases marginally with flight speed.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] However, being an air breathing engine (unlike a conventional rocket) there is a penalty for taking on-board air from the atmosphere.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Although the penalty is zero at static conditions, it rapidly increases with flight speed, causing the net thrust to be eroded.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] As flight speed builds up after take-off, the ram rise in the intake starts to have a significant effect upon nozzle pressure/temperature and intake airflow, causing nozzle gross thrust to climb more rapidly.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] This term now starts to offset the still increasing ram drag, eventually causing net thrust to start to increase.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] In some engines, the net thrust at say Mach 1.0, sea level can even be slightly greater than the static thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Above Mach 1.0, with a subsonic inlet design, shock losses tend to decrease net thrust, however a suitably designed supersonic inlet can give a lower reduction in intake pressure recovery, allowing net thrust to continue to climb in the supersonic regime.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines are usually very reliable and have a very good safety record.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] In some cases in jet engines the conditions in the engine due to airflow entering the engine or other variations can cause the compressor blades to stall.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] When this occurs the pressure in the engine blows out past the blades, and the stall is maintained until the pressure has decreased, and the engine has lost all thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The compressor blades will then usually come out of stall, and re-pressurize the engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] If conditions are not corrected, the cycle will usually repeat.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Depending on the engine this can be highly damaging to the engine and creates worrying vibrations for the crew.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Fan, compressor or turbine blade failures have to be contained within the engine casing.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] To do this the engine has to be designed to pass blade containment tests as specified by certification authorities.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Bird ingestion is the term used when birds enter the intake of a jet engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is a common aircraft safety hazard and has caused fatal accidents.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] In 1988 an Ethiopian Airlines Boeing 737 ingested pigeons into both engines during take-off and then crashed in an attempt to return to the Bahir Dar airport; of the 104 people aboard, 35 died and 21 were injured.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] In another incident in 1995, a Dassault Falcon 20 crashed at a Paris airport during an emergency landing attempt after ingesting lapwings into an engine, which caused an engine failure and a fire in the airplane fuselage; all 10 people on board were killed.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines have to be designed to withstand the ingestion of birds of a specified weight and number, and to not lose more than a specified amount of thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The weight and numbers of birds that can be ingested without hazarding the safe flight of the aircraft are related to the engine intake area.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] In 2009, an Airbus A320 aircraft, US Airways Flight 1549, ingested one Canada goose into each engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The plane ditched in the Hudson River after taking off from LaGuardia International Airport in New York City.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The incident illustrated the hazards of ingesting birds beyond the "designed-for" limit.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The outcome of an ingestion event and whether it causes an accident, be it on a small fast plane, such as military jet fighters, or a large transport, depends on the number and weight of birds and where they strike the fan blade span or the nose cone.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Core damage usually results with impacts near the blade root or on the nose cone.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Few birds fly high, so the greatest risk of a bird ingestion is during takeoff and landing and during low level flying.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] If a jet plane is flying through air contaminated with volcanic ash, there is risk that ingested ash will cause erosion damage to the compressor blades, blockage of fuel nozzle air holes and blockage of the turbine cooling passages.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Some of these effects may cause the engine to surge or flame-out during the flight.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Re-lights are usually successful after flame-outs but with considerable loss of altitude.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] It was the case of British Airways Flight 9 which flew through volcanic dust at 37,000 ft.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] All 4 engines flamed out and re-light attempts were successful at about 13,000 ft.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] One class of failure that has caused accidents is the uncontained failure, where rotating parts of the engine break off and exit through the case.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] These high energy parts can cut fuel and control lines, and can penetrate the cabin.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Although fuel and control lines are usually duplicated for reliability, the crash of United Airlines Flight 232 was caused when hydraulic fluid lines for all three independent hydraulic systems were simultaneously severed by shrapnel from an uncontained engine failure.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Prior to the United 232 crash, the probability of a simultaneous failure of all three hydraulic systems was considered as high as a billion-to-one.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] However, the statistical models used to come up with this figure did not account for the fact that the number-two engine was mounted at the tail close to all the hydraulic lines, nor the possibility that an engine failure would release fragments in multiple directions.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Since then, more modern aircraft engine designs have focused on keeping shrapnel from penetrating the cowling or ductwork, and have increasingly utilized high-strength composite materials to achieve the required penetration resistance while keeping the weight low.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] In 2007 the cost of jet fuel, while highly variable from one airline to another, averaged 26.5% of total operating costs, making it the single largest operating expense for most airlines.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines are usually run on fossil fuels and are thus a source of carbon dioxide in the atmosphere.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines can also run on biofuels or hydrogen, although hydrogen is usually produced from fossil fuels.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] About 7.2% of the oil used in 2004 was consumed by jet engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Some scientists believe that jet engines are also a source of global dimming due to the water vapour in the exhaust causing cloud formations.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Nitrogen compounds are also formed during the combustion process from reactions with atmospheric nitrogen.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] At low altitudes this is not thought to be especially harmful, but for supersonic aircraft that fly in the stratosphere some destruction of ozone may occur.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Sulphates are also emitted if the fuel contains sulphur.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] A ramjet is a form of airbreathing jet engine using the engine's forward motion to compress incoming air, without a rotary compressor.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Ramjets cannot produce thrust at zero airspeed and thus cannot move an aircraft from a standstill.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Ramjets require considerable forward speed to operate well, and as a class work most efficiently at speeds around Mach 3.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] This type of jet can operate up to speeds of Mach 6.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] They consist of three sections; an inlet to compress incoming air, a combustor to inject and combust fuel, and a nozzle to expel the hot gases and produce thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Ramjets require a relatively high speed to efficiently compress the incoming air, so ramjets cannot operate at a standstill and they are most efficient at supersonic speeds.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] A key trait of ramjet engines is that combustion is done at subsonic speeds.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The supersonic incoming air is dramatically slowed through the inlet, where it is then combusted at the much slower, subsonic, speeds.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The faster the incoming air is, however, the less efficient it becomes to slow it to subsonic speeds.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Therefore, ramjet engines are limited to approximately Mach 5.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] They have also been used successfully, though not efficiently, as tip jets on helicopter rotors.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Pulsejets are subsonic engines which also use ram compression, but with intermittent combustion unlike the continuous combustion used in a ramjet.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] They are a quite distinct type of jet engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Scramjets are an evolution of ramjets that are able to operate at much higher speeds than any other kind of airbreathing engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] They share a similar structure with ramjets, being a specially shaped tube that compresses air with no moving parts through ram-air compression.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] They consist of an inlet, a combustor, and a nozzle.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The primary difference between ramjets and scramjets is that scramjets do not slow the oncoming airflow to subsonic speeds for combustion.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Thus, scramjets do not have the diffuser required by ramjets to slow the incoming airflow to subsonic speeds.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Scramjets start working at speeds of at least Mach 4, and have a maximum useful speed of approximately Mach 17.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Due to aerodynamic heating at these high speeds, cooling poses a challenge to engineers.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Since scramjets use supersonic combustion they can operate at speeds above Mach 6 where traditional ramjets are too inefficient.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Very few scramjet engines have ever been built and flown.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] In May 2010 the Boeing X-51 set the endurance record for the longest scramjet burn at over 200 seconds.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Turbojet operation over the complete flight envelope from zero to Mach 3+ requires features to allow the compressor to function properly at the high inlet temperatures beyond Mach 2.5 as well as at low flight speeds.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The J58 compressor solution was to bleed airflow from the 4th compressor stage at speeds above about Mach 2.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The bleed flow, 20% at Mach 3, was returned to the engine via 6 external tubes to cool the afterburner liner and primary nozzle as well as to provide extra air for combustion.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The J58 engine was the only operational turbojet engine, being designed to operate continuously even at maximum afterburning, for Mach 3.2 cruise.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] An alternative solution is seen in a contemporary installation, which did not reach operational status, the Mach 3 GE YJ93/XB-70.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Yet another solution was specified in a proposal for a Mach 3 reconnaissance Phantom.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] This was pre-compressor cooling, albeit available for relatively short duration.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Jet engines can be run on almost any fuel.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Hydrogen is a highly desirable fuel, as, although the energy per mole is not unusually high, the molecule is very much lighter than other molecules.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The energy per kg of hydrogen is twice that of more common fuels and this gives twice the specific impulse.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] In addition, jet engines running on hydrogen are quite easy to build—the first ever turbojet was run on hydrogen.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Also, although not duct engines, hydrogen-fueled rocket engines have seen extensive use.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] However, in almost every other way, hydrogen is problematic.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The downside of hydrogen is its density; in gaseous form the tanks are impractical for flight, but even in the form of liquid hydrogen it has a density one fourteenth that of water.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] It is also deeply cryogenic and requires very significant insulation that precludes it being stored in wings.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The overall vehicle would end up being very large, and difficult for most airports to accommodate.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Finally, pure hydrogen is not found in nature, and must be manufactured either via steam reforming or expensive electrolysis.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] A few experimental hydrogen-powered aircraft have flown with propellers, and jets have been proposed that may be feasible.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Carmichael in 1955 is that hydrogen-fueled engines could theoretically have much higher performance than hydrocarbon-fueled engines if a heat exchanger were used to cool the incoming air.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The low temperature allows lighter materials to be used, a higher mass-flow through the engines, and permits combustors to inject more fuel without overheating the engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] This idea leads to plausible designs like Reaction Engines SABRE, that might permit single-stage-to-orbit launch vehicles, and ATREX, which could permit jet engines to be used up to hypersonic speeds and high altitudes for boosters for launch vehicles.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The idea is also being researched by the EU for a concept to achieve non-stop antipodal supersonic passenger travel at Mach 5 (Reaction Engines A2).
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The **air turborocket** is a form of combined-cycle jet engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The basic layout includes a gas generator, which produces high pressure gas, that drives a turbine/compressor assembly which compresses atmospheric air into a combustion chamber.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] This mixture is then combusted before leaving the device through a nozzle and creating thrust.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] There are different types of air turborockets.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] The various types generally differ in how the gas generator section of the engine functions.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] Air turborockets are often referred to as **turboramjets**, **turboramjet rockets**, **turborocket expanders**, and others.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] As there is no consensus on which names apply to which specific concepts, various sources may use the same name for two different concepts.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] In multiple cases, instead of expressing rotor speeds (N1, N2) as RPM on cockpit displays, pilots are provided with the speeds expressed as a percentage of the design point speed.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] For example, at full power, the N1 might be 101.5% or 100%.
[src:brayton-cycle/airbreathing-jet-engine] This user interface decision has been made as a human factors consideration, since pilots are more likely to notice a problem with a two- or 3-digit percentage (where 100% implies a nominal value) than with a 5-digit RPM.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] "**An Inquiry Concerning the Source of the Heat Which Is Excited by Friction**" is a scientific paper by Benjamin Thompson, Count Rumford, which was published in the Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society in 1798.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] The paper provided a substantial challenge to established theories of heat, and began the 19th century revolution in thermodynamics.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford was an opponent of the caloric theory of heat which held that heat is a fluid that could be neither created nor destroyed.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He had further developed the view that all gases and liquids are absolute non-conductors of heat.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] His views were out of step with the accepted science of the time and the latter theory had particularly been attacked by John Dalton and John Leslie.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford was heavily influenced by the argument from design and it is likely that he wished to grant water a privileged and providential status in the regulation of human life.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Though Rumford was to come to associate heat with motion, there is no evidence that he was committed to the kinetic theory or the principle of *vis viva*.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] In his 1798 paper, Rumford acknowledged that he had predecessors in the notion that heat was a form of motion.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Those predecessors included Francis Bacon, Robert Boyle, Robert Hooke, John Locke, and Henry Cavendish.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford had observed the frictional heat generated by boring out cannon barrels at the arsenal in Munich.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] At that time, cannons were cast at the foundry with an extra section of metal forward of what would become the muzzle, and this section was removed and discarded later in the manufacturing process.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford took an unfinished cannon and modified this section to allow it to be enclosed by a watertight box while a blunted boring tool was used on it.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He showed that water in this box could be boiled within roughly two and a half hours, and that the supply of frictional heat was seemingly inexhaustible.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford confirmed that no physical change had taken place in the material of the cannon by comparing the specific heats of the material machined away and that remaining were the same.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford also argued that the seemingly indefinite generation of heat was incompatible with the caloric theory.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] He contended that the only thing communicated to the barrel was motion.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Rumford made no attempt to further quantify the heat generated or to measure the mechanical equivalent of heat.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Most established scientists, such as William Henry, as well as Thomas Thomson, believed that there was enough uncertainty in the caloric theory to allow its adaptation to account for the new results.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] It had certainly proved robust and adaptable up to that time.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Furthermore, Thomson, Jöns Jakob Berzelius, and Antoine César Becquerel observed that electricity could be indefinitely generated by friction.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] No educated scientist of the time was willing to hold that electricity was not a fluid.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Ultimately, Rumford's claim of the "inexhaustible" supply of heat was a reckless extrapolation from the study.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Charles Haldat made some penetrating criticisms of the reproducibility of Rumford's results and it is possible to see the whole experiment as somewhat tendentious.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] However, the experiment inspired the work of James Prescott Joule in the 1840s.
[src:brayton-cycle/an-inquiry-concerning-the-source-of-the-heat-which-is-excited-by-friction] Joule's more exact measurements were pivotal in establishing the kinetic theory at the expense of caloric.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] The **Armengaud-Lemale gas turbine** was an early experimental turbine engine built by the *Société Anonyme des Turbomoteurs* at their facility in Saint-Denis, Paris during 1906.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] The machine is named after the society's founders, Rene Armengaud and Charles Lemale.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] The 1906 Armengaud-Lemale gas turbine could sustain its own air compression but was too inefficient to produce useful work.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] Although it was unsuccessful as a gas turbine, the combustion chamber design from the 1906 machine was later used successfully in torpedo engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] In 1901, Charles Lemale obtained a patent for a gas turbine and in 1903 he founded the *Société Anonyme des Turbomoteurs* with Rene Armengaud.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] The society proposed a number of new technologies including hollow turbine blades, combustion reheat and compressor stage inter-cooling.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] In 1904 the society built a small proof of concept gas turbine.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] Air was supplied to an oil fueled combustion chamber by a centrifugal compressor at a pressure of 71 psi (4.9 bar).
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] The air fuel mixture was fired by a hot wire with combustion products cooled by water spray.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] Exhaust gasses were expanded in a nozzle before acting on a modified 25 hp (19 kW) de Laval steam turbine with a 6 in (152 mm) wheel which ran at 20,000 rpm.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] In 1906 the society completed a large gas turbine with three gas compressor casings containing a total of 25 centrifugal impellers.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] The compressors were designed by Auguste Rateau and manufactured by Brown, Boveri & Cie in Switzerland.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] These were the first of many centrifugal compressors manufactured by Brown, Boveri & Cie.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] Due to the state of metallurgy in 1906, interstage turbine temperatures had to be kept below 878 °F (470 °C) to avoid damaging turbine wheels.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] To maintain acceptable temperatures a steady stream of water was injected into the combustion chamber.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] Low turbine admission temperatures and the relatively poor efficiency of early centrifugal compressors gave the Armengaud-Lemale gas turbine a low thermal efficiency.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] In its final form, the Armengaud-Lemale machine was efficient enough to power its own air compressors but could do little else and was not viable as a commercial power source.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] It was later calculated that to achieve an overall efficiency of just 5% with a compressor efficiency of 68% and a turbine efficiency of 78% would have required a combustion temperature of 1,500 °F (816 °C) which was not possible given the technology available in 1906.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] Following their work on the Armengaud-Lemale turbine, Brown, Boveri & Cie went onto develop a series of industrial centrifugal compressors and eventually built and tested the world's first gas turbine power station at Neuchâtel, Switzerland in 1939.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] The 1906 machine was the last large gas turbine built by the *Société Anonyme des Turbomoteurs.* The society ceased all work on gas turbines after the death of Rene Armengaud in 1909.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] The combustion chamber of the 1906 gas turbine was successfully developed, and licensed by the society, for use in naval torpedoes.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] Kerosene was injected and burned in a compressed air stream increasing the pressure actuating the torpedo's propelling engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] The Armengaud-Lemale combustion chamber was ideal for this application owing to the availability of seawater for cooling.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] Test data published by the *Société Anonyme des Turbomoteurs*.
[src:brayton-cycle/armengaud-lemale-gas-turbine] Run took place with a quoted ambient temperature of 64 °F (18 °C).
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The **Atkinson-cycle engine** is a type of internal combustion engine invented by James Atkinson in 1882.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Atkinson cycle is designed to provide efficiency at the expense of power density.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] A variation of this approach is used in some modern automobile engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] While originally seen exclusively in hybrid electric applications such as the earlier-generation Toyota Prius, later hybrids and some non-hybrid vehicles now feature engines with variable valve timing.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Variable valve timing can run in the Atkinson cycle as a part-time operating regimen, giving good economy while running in Atkinson cycle mode, and conventional power density when running in conventional Otto cycle mode.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson produced three different designs that had a short compression stroke and a longer expansion stroke.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The first Atkinson-cycle engine, the *differential engine*, used opposed pistons.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The second and best-known design was the *cycle engine*, which used an over-center arm to create four piston strokes in one crankshaft revolution.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This unusual reciprocating engine had the intake, compression, power, and exhaust strokes of the four-stroke cycle in a single turn of the crankshaft, and was designed to avoid infringing certain patents covering Otto-cycle engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's third and final engine, the *utilite engine*, operated much like a two-stroke engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Apart from the features implemented to avoid Otto patents, the truly unique Atkinson's design is that the engines have an expansion stroke that is longer than the compression stroke, and by this method the engine achieves greater thermal efficiency than a traditional piston engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's engines were produced by the British Gas Engine Company and also licensed to other overseas manufacturers.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Many modern engines now use a crankshaft center-line offset from the cylinder center-line (making them desaxe engines) and/or unconventional valve timing to produce the effect of a shorter compression stroke/longer power stroke.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Miller applied this technique to the four-stroke engine, so it is sometimes referred as the Atkinson/Miller cycle, US patent 2817322 dated Dec 24, 1957.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] In 1888, Charon filed a French patent and displayed an engine at the Paris Exhibition in 1889.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Charon gas engine (four-stroke) used a similar cycle to Miller, but without a supercharger.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] It is referred to as the "Charon cycle".
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Hugo Güldner argued in his 1914 book that Körting was the first firm to build a gas engine with a short compression stroke and a longer expansion phase in 1891, based on a design first proposed by Otto Köhler in 1887.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This engine also had an engine-load dependent valve train which increased the intake and compression stroke with increasing engine load.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] On the other hand, the compression was decreasing at low and medium loads, which ultimately reduced the efficiency.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Roy Fedden, at Bristol, tested an arrangement in the Bristol Jupiter IV engine in 1928, with variable retard timing allowing part of the charge to be blown back into the intake manifold, in order to have sustainable reduced operation pressures during takeoff.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Modern engine designers are realizing the potential fuel-efficiency improvements the Atkinson-type cycle can provide.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The first implementation of the Atkinson cycle was in 1882; unlike later versions, it was arranged as an opposed-piston engine, the Atkinson differential engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Thus, in each revolution, one piston provided a compression stroke and a power stroke, and then the other piston provided an exhaust stroke and a charging stroke.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The next engine designed by Atkinson in 1887 was named the "Cycle Engine" This engine used poppet valves, a cam, and an over-center arm to produce four piston strokes for every revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The intake and compression strokes were significantly shorter than the expansion and exhaust strokes.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The "Cycle" engines were produced and sold for several years by the British Engine Company.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson also licensed production to other manufacturers.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Sizes ranged from a few up to 100 horsepower.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's third design was named the "Utilite Engine".
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson's "Cycle" engine was efficient; however, its linkage was difficult to balance for high speed operation.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Atkinson realized an improvement was needed to make his cycle more applicable as a higher-speed engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Utilite operates much like a standard two-stroke except that the exhaust port is located at about the middle of the stroke.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] During the expansion/power stroke, a cam-operated valve (which remains closed until the piston nears the end of the stroke) prevents pressure from escaping as the piston moves past the exhaust port.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The exhaust valve is opened near the bottom of the stroke; it remains open as the piston heads back toward compression, letting fresh air charge the cylinder and exhaust escape until the port is covered by the piston.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] After the exhaust port is covered the piston begins to compress the remaining air in the cylinder.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] A small piston fuel pump injects liquid during compression.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The ignition source was likely a hot tube as in Atkinson's other engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This design resulted in a two-stroke engine with a short compression and longer expansion stroke.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Utilite Engine tested as even more efficient than Atkinson's previous "differential" and "cycle" designs.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Very few were produced, and none are known to survive.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] No US patent for the Utilite Engine is known.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] In the late 20th century, the term "Atkinson cycle" began to be used to describe a modified Otto-cycle engine—in which the intake valve is held open longer than normal, allowing a reverse flow of intake air into the intake manifold.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This "simulated" Atkinson cycle is most notably used in the Toyota 1NZ-FXE engine from the early Prius and the Toyota Dynamic Force engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The effective compression ratio is reduced—for the time the air is escaping the cylinder freely rather than being compressed—but the *expansion* ratio is unchanged (i.e., the compression ratio is smaller than the expansion ratio).
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The goal of the modern Atkinson cycle is to make the pressure in the combustion chamber at the end of the power stroke equal to atmospheric pressure.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] When this occurs, all available energy has been obtained from the combustion process.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] For any given portion of air, the greater expansion ratio converts more energy from heat to useful mechanical energy—meaning the engine is more efficient.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The disadvantage of the four-stroke Atkinson-cycle engine versus the more common Otto-cycle engine is reduced power density.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Due to a smaller portion of the compression stroke being devoted to compressing the intake air, an Atkinson-cycle engine does not take in as much air as would a similarly designed and sized Otto-cycle engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Four-stroke engines of this type that use the same type of intake valve motion but also utilize forced induction to make up for the loss of power density are known as Miller-cycle engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The Atkinson cycle can be used in a rotary engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] In this configuration, an increase in both power and efficiency can be achieved when compared to the Otto cycle.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This type of engine retains the one power phase per revolution, together with the different compression and expansion volumes of the original Atkinson cycle.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Exhaust gases are expelled from the engine by compressed-air scavenging.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This modification of the Atkinson cycle allows the use of alternative fuels such as diesel and hydrogen.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] Disadvantages of this design include the requirement that rotor tips seal very tightly on the outer housing wall and the mechanical losses suffered through friction between rapidly oscillating parts of irregular shape.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] See *§ External links* below for more information.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] While a modified Otto-cycle piston engine using the Atkinson cycle provides good fuel efficiency, it is at the expense of a lower power-per-displacement as compared to a traditional four-stroke engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] If demand for more power is intermittent, the power of the engine can be supplemented by an electric motor during times when more power is needed.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This forms the basis of an Atkinson cycle-based hybrid electric drivetrain.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] These electric motors can be used independently of, or in combination with, the Atkinson-cycle engine, to provide the most efficient means of producing the desired power.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] This drive-train first entered production in late 1997 in the first-generation Toyota Prius.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The 1887 patent (US 367496) describes the mechanical linkages necessary to obtain all four strokes of the four-stroke cycle for a gas engine within one revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] There is also a reference to an 1886 Atkinson patent (US 336505), which describes an opposed-piston gas engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/atkinson-cycle] The British patent for the "Utilite'" is from 1892 (#2492).
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The **Brayton cycle**, also known as the **Joule cycle**, is a thermodynamic cycle that describes the operation of certain heat engines that have air or some other gas as their working fluid.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] It is characterized by isentropic compression and expansion, and isobaric heat addition and rejection, though practical engines have adiabatic rather than isentropic steps.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The most common current application is in airbreathing jet engines and gas turbine engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The engine cycle is named after George Brayton (1830–1892), the American engineer, who developed the Brayton Ready Motor in 1872, using a piston compressor and piston expander.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] An engine using the cycle was originally proposed and patented by Englishman John Barber in 1791, using a reciprocating compressor and a turbine expander.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] There are two main types of Brayton cycles: closed and open.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In a closed cycle, the working gas stays inside the engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Heat is introduced with a heat exchanger or external combustion and expelled with a heat exchanger.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] With the open cycle, air from the atmosphere is drawn in, goes through three steps of the cycle, and is expelled again to the atmosphere.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Open cycles allow for internal combustion.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Although the cycle is open, it is conventionally assumed for the purposes of thermodynamic analysis that the exhaust gases are reused in the intake, enabling analysis as a closed cycle.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1872, George Brayton applied for a patent for his "Ready Motor", a reciprocating heat engine operating on a gas power cycle.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The engine was a two-stroke and produced power on every revolution.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Brayton engines used a separate piston compressor and piston expander, with compressed air heated by internal fire as it entered the expander cylinder.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The first versions of the Brayton engine were vapor engines which mixed fuel with air as it entered the compressor; town gas was used or a surface carburetor was also used for mobile operation .
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The fuel / air was contained in a reservoir / tank and then it was admitted to the expansion cylinder and burned.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] As the fuel/air mixture entered the expansion cylinder, it was ignited by a pilot flame.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] A screen was used to prevent the fire from entering or returning to the reservoir.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In early versions of the engine, this screen sometimes failed and an explosion would occur.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1874, Brayton solved the explosion problem by adding the fuel just prior to the expander cylinder.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The engine now used heavier fuels such as kerosene and fuel oil.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Brayton produced and sold "Ready Motors" to perform a variety of tasks like water pumping, mill operation, running generators, and marine propulsion.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The "Ready Motors" were produced from 1872 to sometime in the 1880s; several hundred such motors were likely produced during this time period.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Brayton licensed the design to Simone in the UK.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Many variations of the layout were used; some were single-acting and some were double-acting.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Some had under walking beams; others had overhead walking beams.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Both horizontal and vertical models were built.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Sizes ranged from less than one to over 40 horsepower.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Critics of the time claimed the engines ran smoothly and had a reasonable efficiency.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Brayton-cycle engines were some of the first internal combustion engines used for motive power.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1875, John Holland used a Brayton engine to power the world's first self-propelled submarine (Holland boat #1).
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1879, a Brayton engine was used to power a second submarine, the *Fenian Ram*.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] John Philip Holland's submarines are preserved in the Paterson Museum in the Old Great Falls Historic District of Paterson, New Jersey.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Selden patented the first internal combustion automobile.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Inspired by the internal combustion engine invented by Brayton displayed at the Centennial Exposition in Philadelphia in 1876, Selden patented a four-wheel car working on a smaller, lighter, multicylinder version.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] He then filed a series of amendments to his application which stretched out the legal process, resulting in a delay of 16 years before the patent was granted on November 5, 1895.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1903, Selden sued Ford for patent infringement and Henry Ford fought the Selden patent until 1911.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Selden had never actually produced a working car, so during the trial, two machines were constructed according to the patent drawings.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Ford argued his cars used the four-stroke Alphonse Beau de Rochas cycle or Otto cycle and not the Brayton-cycle engine used in the Selden auto.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Ford won the appeal of the original case.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1887, Brayton developed and patented a four-stroke direct-injection oil engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The fuel system used a variable-quantity pump and liquid-fuel, high-pressure, spray-type injection.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The liquid was forced through a spring-loaded, relief-type valve (injector) which caused the fuel to become divided into small droplets.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Injection was timed to occur at or near the peak of the compression stroke.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] A platinum igniter provided the source of ignition.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In this manner, the engine fired on every power stroke and speed and output were controlled solely by the quantity of fuel injected.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 1890, Brayton developed and patented a four-stroke, air-blast oil engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The fuel system delivered a variable quantity of vaporized fuel to the center of the cylinder under pressure at or near the peak of the compression stroke.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The ignition source was an igniter made from platinum wire.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] A variable-quantity injection pump provided the fuel to an injector where it was mixed with air as it entered the cylinder.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] A small crank-driven compressor provided the source for air.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] This engine also used the lean-burn system.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Rudolf Diesel originally proposed a very high compression, constant-temperature cycle where the heat of compression would exceed the heat of combustion, but after several years of experiments, he realized that the constant-temperature cycle would not work in a piston engine.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Early Diesel engines use an air blast system which was pioneered by Brayton in 1890.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Consequently, these early engines use the constant-pressure cycle.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] A Brayton-type engine consists of three components: a compressor, a mixing chamber, and an expander.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Modern Brayton engines are almost always a turbine type, although Brayton only made piston engines.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In the original 19th-century Brayton engine, ambient air is drawn into a piston compressor, where it is compressed; ideally an isentropic process.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The compressed air then passes through a mixing chamber where fuel is added, an isobaric process.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The pressurized air and fuel mixture is then ignited in an expansion cylinder and energy is released, causing the heated air and combustion products to expand through a piston/cylinder, another ideally isentropic process.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Some of the work extracted by the piston/cylinder is used to drive the compressor through a crankshaft arrangement.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Gas turbine engines are also Brayton engines, with three components: an air compressor, a combustion chamber, and a gas turbine.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] 2. isobaric process – the compressed air then passes through a combustion chamber, where fuel is burned, heating that air—a constant-pressure process, since the chamber is open to flow in and out.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] 3. isentropic process – the heated, pressurized air then gives up its energy, expanding through a turbine (or series of turbines).
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Some of the work extracted by the turbine is used to drive the compressor.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] 4. isobaric process – heat rejection (in the atmosphere).
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Since neither the compression nor the expansion can be truly isentropic, losses through the compressor and the expander represent sources of inescapable working inefficiencies.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In general, increasing the compression ratio is the most direct way to increase the overall power output of a Brayton system.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Figure 1 indicates how the cycle efficiency changes with an increase in pressure ratio.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Figure 2 indicates how the specific power output changes with an increase in the gas turbine inlet temperature for two different pressure ratio values.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The highest gas temperature in the cycle occurs where work transfer to the high pressure turbine (rotor inlet) takes place.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] This is lower than the highest gas temperature in the engine (combustion zone).
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The maximum cycle temperature is limited by the turbine materials and required turbine life.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] This also limits the pressure ratios that can be used in the cycle.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] For a fixed-turbine inlet temperature, the net work output per cycle increases with the pressure ratio (thus the thermal efficiency) and the net work output.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] With less work output per cycle, a larger mass flow rate (thus a larger system) is needed to maintain the same power output, which may not be economical.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In most common designs, the pressure ratio of a gas turbine ranges from about 11 to 16.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] A closed Brayton cycle recirculates the working fluid; the air expelled from the turbine is reintroduced into the compressor, this cycle uses a heat exchanger to heat the working fluid instead of an internal combustion chamber.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The closed Brayton cycle is used, for example, in closed-cycle gas turbines for power generation in space.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] In 2002, a hybrid open solar Brayton cycle was operated for the first time consistently and effectively with relevant papers published, in the frame of the EU SOLGATE program.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The air was heated from 570 to over 1000K into the combustor chamber.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Further hybridization was achieved during the EU Solhyco project running a hybridized Brayton cycle with solar energy and biodiesel only.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] This technology was scaled up to 4.6 MW within the project Solugas located near Seville, where it is currently demonstrated at precommercial scale.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] A Brayton cycle that is driven in reverse uses work to move heat.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] This makes it a form of gas refrigeration cycle.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] When air is the working fluid, it is known as the Bell Coleman cycle.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] It is also used in the LNG industry for subcooling LNG using power from a gas turbine to drive the compressor.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] This is an open Brayton cycle which also generates work from heat, but with a different order of the stages.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] Incoming air is first heated at atmospheric pressure, and then passes through the turbine, generating work.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The gas, now at a pressure lower than atmospheric, is cooled in a heat exchanger.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] The compressor raises the pressure again so the gas can be expelled to the atmosphere.
[src:brayton-cycle/brayton-cycle] NASA is considering the Brayton cycle for its lunar nuclear reactor to be launched in 2030.
